                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_kxy1fkvr">
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_fbu7dr62">
                    To formatively assess individual learner understanding of reflection and congruence in real-life contexts.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_wze1frlh">
                <title>Learning Experience</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_5dok22gi">
                    Learners complete the following exit-ticket questions independently.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <exercises xml:id="reflection-and-congruency-in-real-life">
        <title>Exercise</title>
        <exercise xml:id="auto_6l8y4921">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_8o93k7sa">
                    A landscape designer places a rectangular flower bed with vertices at <m>P(−5, 1), Q(−1, 1), R(−1, 4), S(−5, 4)</m>. 
                    The central pathway is along the y-axis. 
                    Find the coordinates of the reflected flower bed and prove the two beds are congruent.

                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_fntj1pqq">
                    Reflected vertices: <m>P′(5, 1), Q′(1, 1), R′(1, 4), S′(5, 4)</m>. 
               
                        <m>PQ = P′Q′ = 4, QR = Q′R′ = 3, RS = R′S′ = 4, SP = S′P′ = 3</m>.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_usb40mzw">
                     All corresponding sides equal → congruent by SSS. (Also, all angles are 90° in both rectangles.)

                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise xml:id="auto_kengktrl">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_40wi299d">
                    A school building has a symmetric facade. The left half has a window at <m>W(−4, 6)</m> and a door at <m>D(−2, 0)</m>. The axis of symmetry is <m>x = 0</m>. 
                    Where are the corresponding window and door on the right half?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_59e72g6b">
                    Reflecting across <m>x = 0: W′(4, 6)</m> and <m>D′(2, 0)</m>. The window and door on the right half are at <m>(4, 6)</m> and <m>(2, 0)</m> respectively.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise xml:id="auto_cdg6pjtm">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_tmo8t0c6">
                    Explain why a butterfly's wings demonstrate both reflection and congruence. Identify the mirror line and state which congruence criterion you would use to prove the wings are congruent.

                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_4iifwi24">
                    A butterfly's body is the mirror line (axis of symmetry). The left wing is a reflection of the right wing across this line. The wings are congruent because corresponding measurements (wingspan, vein patterns, colour patches) are equal. SSS criterion: all corresponding lengths on both wings are equal.

                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise xml:id="auto_2im8rvdj">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_ff2o92dc">
                  A garden designer wants to place four identical triangular flower beds in a pattern with two lines of symmetry (the x-axis and the y-axis). If one flower bed has vertices at <m>(1, 1), (3, 1)</m>, and <m>(2, 4)</m>, find the vertices of the other three flower beds.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_q8yn7u05">
                    Reflect across y-axis: <m>(-1, 1), (-3, 1), (-2, 4)</m>. 
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_k82qbvet">
                    Reflect across x-axis: <m>(1, −1), (3, −1), (2, −4)</m>. 
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_gpp9ampe">
                    Reflect across both: <m>(−1, −1), (−3, −1), (−2, −4)</m>. 
                    All four triangles are congruent by SSS.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

